---
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Icon from "../components/Icon.astro";
import MiteTerm from "../components/MiteTerm.astro";
import MiteText from "../components/MiteText.astro";
import MiteWord from "../components/MiteWord.astro";
import { GITHUB_URL, RELEASES_URL, SITE_DESCRIPTION } from "../data/sentences";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const FAQ_TITLE = "Mite FAQ: private, local Japanese OCR for Windows";
---

<Base title={FAQ_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}>
  <Header />
  <main class="container faq">
    <div class="faq-inner">
      <a href="/" class="mono faq-back">
        <Icon name="arrow-left" size={16} /> Back to home
      </a>
      <h1 class="faq-title">Questions, answered plainly.</h1>
      <p class="measure faq-lede">
        What <MiteTerm /> is, where it runs, and what it does and does not do.
      </p>

      <div class="prose-mite faq-groups">
        <section>
          <h2 class="tick-label faq-group-title">What it does</h2>
          <dl class="faq-list">
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q">
                <MiteText text="Does Mite translate whole sentences?" />
              </dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                No, and that is on purpose. <MiteTerm /> is a reading aid, not a
                machine translator. It gives you the reading, the dictionary form,
                English glosses, inflection notes, and furigana for each word, so
                you keep reading the Japanese yourself instead of replacing it with
                English.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q">
                <MiteText text="How is this different from Yomitan or 10ten?" />
              </dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                Those are excellent browser extensions, and for ordinary web pages
                they are the better fit: they read the page's own text directly.
                <MiteTerm />'s niche is everything outside the browser: native games,
                visual novels, and apps a browser extension can never reach.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q">
                <MiteText text="Will the overlay get in the way of the game?" />
              </dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                The overlay is layered and click-through. It does not steal focus or
                interrupt game input: your clicks and keys pass straight through to
                the game. <MiteTerm /> sits unnoticed until you want a reading, then
                gets out of the way.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="What is it built on?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                PP-OCRv5 detection and recognition models run through ONNX Runtime;
                Lindera segments the recognized text into words; and definitions
                come from JMdict, ordered by JPDB frequency so the most likely
                meaning leads.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="tick-label faq-group-title">Privacy and trust</h2>
          <dl class="faq-list">
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="Is Mite really fully local?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                Yes. Capture, OCR, segmentation, and dictionary lookup all run on
                your machine. There is no cloud OCR and no network round-trip:
                nothing about what you are reading is sent off the device.
                Because <MiteTerm /> is open source under AGPL-3.0, you can read the
                code and confirm it yourself.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="Is it free and open source?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                Both. <MiteTerm /> is licensed AGPL-3.0. The capture path, the OCR
                models, the segmentation, and the lookup are all open to read and
                audit.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="tick-label faq-group-title">Where it runs</h2>
          <dl class="faq-list">
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q">
                <MiteText text="Which platforms does Mite support?" />
              </dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                <MiteTerm /> is Windows-first (Windows 10 and 11) and optimized for
                NVIDIA hardware. It is not built for macOS or Linux. The overlay is
                a native Win32 layer, so the experience is specific to Windows.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="Do I need an NVIDIA GPU?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                An NVIDIA GPU is recommended for the fastest path. <MiteTerm /> uses
                TensorRT where it can, falls back to CUDA, and falls back again to
                CPU, so it runs without a dedicated GPU, just not as quickly as the
                reference numbers.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="Which apps does it work with?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                <MiteTerm /> captures the pixels of a target window, so it does not
                need any cooperation from the app it reads. That covers native
                games, visual novels, manga and comic readers, and video (paused or
                live). If Windows can put it on screen, <MiteTerm /> can read it.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="tick-label faq-group-title">Speed and accuracy</h2>
          <dl class="faq-list">
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="How fast is it?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                On the reference NVIDIA setup, a fresh full-screen read of a 4K game
                frame takes about 200ms (p95, on the native TensorRT path). Your
                hardware sets the exact number.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="How accurate is the OCR?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                Measured against several hundred hand-checked 4K screenshots, about
                94 of every 100 text lines are read perfectly, and roughly one
                character in eighty is wrong or missing. Mistakes concentrate in
                tiny, faint, or heavily stylized text; ordinary dialogue and menus
                read very reliably.
              </dd>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q">
                <MiteText text="What happens when it gets a character wrong?" />
              </dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                When a misread happens, it usually shows up as an unknown word
                rather than a confident wrong definition, so a definition
                <MiteTerm /> shows is one it actually found.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </section>

        <section>
          <h2 class="tick-label faq-group-title">Getting it</h2>
          <dl class="faq-list">
            <div class="faq-item">
              <dt class="faq-q"><MiteText text="How do I install Mite?" /></dt>
              <dd class="measure faq-a">
                <MiteTerm /> is open source, and the canonical setup path is the
                repository's bootstrap script: clone the repo, run <code
                  class="mono faq-code">bootstrap-dev.ps1</code> once in PowerShell,
                and you are reading. See <a
                  href={GITHUB_URL}
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noreferrer">the GitHub repository</a> for the full quick
                start.
              </dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
        </section>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-cta">
        <a href={GITHUB_URL} class="btn btn-primary" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          <Icon name="github" size={16} /> View on GitHub
        </a>
        <a href={RELEASES_URL} class="btn btn-ghost" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          Get <MiteWord />
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>

<style>
  .faq {
    padding-block: 4rem;
  }
  .faq-inner {
    max-width: 48rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
  }
  .faq-back {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-muted);
    transition: color 0.16s var(--ease-out);
  }
  .faq-back:hover {
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
  .faq-title {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    font-size: clamp(2.25rem, 5vw, 3.25rem);
    font-weight: 800;
  }
  .faq-lede {
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    color: var(--color-ink-2);
  }
  .faq-groups {
    margin-top: 3.5rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 3.5rem;
  }
  .faq-group-title {
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
  }
  .faq-list {
    margin: 0;
  }
  .faq-item {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-line);
    padding-block: 1.5rem;
  }
  .faq-q {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
  .faq-a {
    margin: 0.625rem 0 0;
    color: var(--color-ink-2);
  }
  .faq-code {
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }
  .faq-cta {
    margin-top: 4rem;
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-line);
    padding-top: 2.5rem;
  }

  /* Prose link treatment, scoped to the FAQ body. */
  .prose-mite {
    color: var(--color-ink-2);
  }
  .prose-mite a {
    color: var(--color-accent-2);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
    text-decoration-color: color-mix(
      in oklch,
      var(--color-accent) 40%,
      transparent
    );
  }
  .prose-mite a:hover {
    text-decoration-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  @media (min-width: 640px) {
    .faq {
      padding-block: 6rem;
    }
  }
</style>
